solutions.content:
It does't matter which numbers we give out. It is the frequencies of numbers that tell whether we can give out that particular number or not. 

The key for this to get accepted is processing quantity requests in decreasing order.

```
    public boolean canDistribute(int[] nums, int[] quantity) {
        // frequency of numbers in nums array
        int[] freq = new int[1001]; // 1 <= nums[i] <= 1000
        int count = 0;
        for (int num : nums) {
            freq[num]++;
            if (freq[num] == 1) count++;
        }

        // stores frequencies of unique numbers appearing in nums.
        int[] numFreq = new int[count];
        int idx = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < freq.length; i++) {
            if (freq[i] == 0) continue; // i didn't occur in nums array.
            numFreq[idx++] = freq[i];
        }

        // without this sort, we get TLE. couldn't figure this during contest. damn it!
        // Processing large quantity requests first reduces recursion tree size.
        Arrays.sort(quantity);
        // Java doesn't have sort ints in decreasing order. So, we will process from end.
        return distribute(numFreq, quantity, quantity.length-1);
    }

    private boolean distribute(int[] numFreq, int[] quantity, int idx) {
        // try all num frequencies which can satisfy quantity[idx]
        boolean result = false;
        for (int i = 0; i < numFreq.length; i++) {
            if (numFreq[i] >= quantity[idx]) {
                numFreq[i] -= quantity[idx];
                result = idx == 0 ? true : distribute(numFreq, quantity, idx-1);
                if (result) break;
                numFreq[i] += quantity[idx]; // backtrack. it didn't work.
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
